# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: do-254
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] An **application-specific integrated circuit** (**ASIC** /ˈeɪsɪk/) is an integrated circuit (IC) chip customized for a particular use, rather than intended for general-purpose use, such as a chip designed to run in a digital voice recorder or a high-efficiency video codec.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Application-specific standard product chips are intermediate between ASICs and industry standard integrated circuits like the 7400 series or the 4000 series.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] ASIC chips are typically fabricated using metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) technology, as MOS integrated circuit chips.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] As feature sizes have shrunk and chip design tools improved over the years, the maximum complexity (and hence functionality) possible in an ASIC has grown from 5,000 logic gates to over 100 million.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Modern ASICs often include entire microprocessors, memory blocks including ROM, RAM, EEPROM, flash memory and other large building blocks.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Such an ASIC is often termed a SoC (system-on-chip).
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Designers of digital ASICs often use a hardware description language (HDL), such as Verilog or VHDL, to describe the functionality of ASICs.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Field-programmable gate arrays (FPGA) are the modern-day technology improvement on breadboards, meaning that they are not made to be application-specific as opposed to ASICs.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Programmable logic blocks and programmable interconnects allow the same FPGA to be used in many different applications.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] For smaller designs or lower production volumes, FPGAs may be more cost-effective than an ASIC design, even in production.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The non-recurring engineering (NRE) cost of an ASIC can run into the millions of dollars.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Therefore, device manufacturers typically prefer FPGAs for prototyping and devices with low production volume and ASICs for very large production volumes where NRE costs can be amortized across many devices.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] By 1967, Ferranti and Interdesign were manufacturing early bipolar gate arrays.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In 1967, Fairchild Semiconductor introduced the Micromatrix family of bipolar diode–transistor logic (DTL) and transistor–transistor logic (TTL) arrays.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor (CMOS) technology opened the door to the broad commercialization of gate arrays.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The first CMOS gate arrays were developed by Robert Lipp, in 1974 for International Microcircuits, Inc.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) standard-cell technology was introduced by Fairchild and Motorola, under the trade names Micromosaic and Polycell, in the 1970s.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This technology was later successfully commercialized by VLSI Technology (founded 1979) and LSI Logic (1981).
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] A successful commercial application of gate array circuitry was found in the low-end 8-bit ZX81 and ZX Spectrum personal computers, introduced in 1981 and 1982.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] These were used by Sinclair Research (UK) essentially as a low-cost I/O solution aimed at handling the computer's graphics.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Customization occurred by varying a metal interconnect mask.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Gate arrays had complexities of up to a few thousand gates; this is now called mid-scale integration.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Later versions became more generalized, with different base dies customized by both metal and polysilicon layers.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Some base dies also include random-access memory (RAM) elements.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In the mid-1980s, a designer would choose an ASIC manufacturer and implement their design using the design tools available from the manufacturer.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] While third-party design tools were available, there was not an effective link from the third-party design tools to the layout and actual semiconductor process performance characteristics of the various ASIC manufacturers.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Most designers used factory-specific tools to complete the implementation of their designs.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] A solution to this problem, which also yielded a much higher density device, was the implementation of standard cells.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Every ASIC manufacturer could create functional blocks with known electrical characteristics, such as propagation delay, capacitance and inductance, that could also be represented in third-party tools.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Standard-cell design is the utilization of these functional blocks to achieve very high gate density and good electrical performance.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Standard-cell design is intermediate between § Gate-array and semi-custom design and § Full-custom design in terms of its non-recurring engineering and recurring component costs as well as performance and speed of development (including time to market).
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] By the late 1990s, logic synthesis tools became available.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Such tools could compile HDL descriptions into a gate-level netlist.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Register-transfer level (RTL) design**: The design team constructs a description of an ASIC to achieve these goals using a hardware description language.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This process is similar to writing a computer program in a high-level language.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Functional verification**: Suitability for purpose is verified by functional verification.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This may include such techniques as logic simulation through test benches, formal verification, emulation, or creating and evaluating an equivalent pure software model, as in Simics.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Each verification technique has advantages and disadvantages, and most often several methods are used together for ASIC verification.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Unlike most FPGAs, ASICs cannot be reprogrammed once fabricated and therefore ASIC designs that are not completely correct are much more costly, increasing the need for full test coverage.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Logic synthesis**: Logic synthesis transforms the RTL design into a large collection called of lower-level constructs called standard cells.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] These constructs are taken from a standard-cell library consisting of pre-characterized collections of logic gates performing specific functions.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The standard cells are typically specific to the planned manufacturer of the ASIC.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The resulting collection of standard cells and the needed electrical connections between them is called a gate-level netlist.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Placement**: The gate-level netlist is next processed by a placement tool which places the standard cells onto a region of an integrated circuit die representing the final ASIC.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The placement tool attempts to find an optimized placement of the standard cells, subject to a variety of specified constraints.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Routing**: An electronics routing tool takes the physical placement of the standard cells and uses the netlist to create the electrical connections between them.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Since the search space is large, this process will produce a "sufficient" rather than "globally optimal" solution.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The output is a file which can be used to create a set of photomasks enabling a semiconductor fabrication facility, commonly called a "fab" or "foundry" to manufacture physical integrated circuits.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Placement and routing are closely interrelated and are collectively called place and route in electronics design.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] While Logic synthesis, Placement, and Routing are supported by electronic design automation tools, these stages require significant designer guidance and iteration.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Designers provide constraints derived from requirements engineering and RTL design, including timing requirements, floorplans, power budgets, and area restrictions.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Multiple tool iterations are typically necessary to meet performance, power, and area objectives, often requiring manual optimization and refinement that extends design cycle time considerably.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Sign-off**: Given the final layout, circuit extraction computes the parasitic resistances and capacitances.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In the case of a digital circuit, this will then be further mapped into delay information from which the circuit performance can be estimated, usually by static timing analysis.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This, and other final tests such as design rule checking and power analysis collectively called signoff are intended to ensure that the device will function correctly over all extremes of the process, voltage and temperature.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] When this testing is complete the photomask information is released for chip fabrication.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] These steps, implemented with a level of skill common in the industry, almost always produce a final device that correctly implements the original design, unless flaws are later introduced by the physical fabrication process.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The design steps also called design flow, are common to standard product design.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The significant difference is that standard-cell design uses the manufacturer's cell libraries that have been used in potentially hundreds of other design implementations and therefore are of much lower risk than a full custom design.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Standard cells produce a design density that is cost-effective, and they can also integrate IP cores and static random-access memory (SRAM) effectively, unlike gate arrays.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Gate array design is a manufacturing method in which diffused layers, each consisting of transistors and other active devices, are predefined and electronics wafers containing such devices are "held in stock" or unconnected prior to the metallization stage of the fabrication process.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The physical design process defines the interconnections of these layers for the final device.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] For most ASIC manufacturers, this consists of between two and nine metal layers with each layer running perpendicular to the one below it.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Non-recurring engineering costs are much lower than full custom designs, as photolithographic masks are required only for the metal layers.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Production cycles are much shorter, as metallization is a comparatively quick process; thereby accelerating time to market.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Gate-array ASICs are always a compromise between rapid design and performance as mapping a given design onto what a manufacturer held as a stock wafer never gives 100% circuit utilization.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Often difficulties in routing the interconnect require migration onto a larger array device with a consequent increase in the piece part price.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] These difficulties are often a result of the layout EDA software used to develop the interconnect.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Pure, logic-only gate-array design is rarely implemented by circuit designers today, having been almost entirely replaced by field-programmable devices.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The most prominent of such devices are field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs) which can be programmed by the user and thus offer minimal tooling charges, non-recurring engineering, only marginally increased piece part cost, and comparable performance.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Today, gate arrays are evolving into structured ASICs that consist of a large IP core like a CPU, digital signal processor units, peripherals, standard interfaces, integrated memories, SRAM, and a block of reconfigurable, uncommitted logic.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In their frequent usages in the field, the terms "gate array" and "semi-custom" are synonymous when referring to ASICs.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Process engineers more commonly use the term "semi-custom", while "gate-array" is more commonly used by logic (or gate-level) designers.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] By contrast, full-custom ASIC design defines all the photolithographic layers of the device.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Full-custom design is used for both ASIC design and for standard product design.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The benefits of full-custom design include reduced area (and therefore recurring component cost), performance improvements, and also the ability to integrate analog components and other pre-designed—and thus fully verified—components, such as microprocessor cores, that form a system on a chip.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The disadvantages of full-custom design can include increased manufacturing and design time, increased non-recurring engineering costs, more complexity in the computer-aided design (CAD) and electronic design automation systems, and a much higher skill requirement on the part of the design team.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] For digital-only designs, however, "standard-cell" cell libraries, together with modern CAD systems, can offer considerable performance/cost benefits with low risk.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Automated layout tools are quick and easy to use and also offer the possibility to "hand-tweak" or manually optimize any performance-limiting aspect of the design.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This is designed by using basic logic gates, circuits or layout specially for a design.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This is effectively the same definition as a gate array.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] What distinguishes a structured ASIC from a gate array is that in a gate array, the predefined metal layers serve to make manufacturing turnaround faster.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In a structured ASIC, the use of predefined metallization is primarily to reduce cost of the mask sets as well as making the design cycle time significantly shorter.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] For example, in a cell-based or gate-array design the user must often design power, clock, and test structures themselves.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] By contrast, these are predefined in most structured ASICs and therefore can save time and expense for the designer compared to gate-array based designs.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Likewise, the design tools used for structured ASIC can be substantially lower cost and easier (faster) to use than cell-based tools, because they do not have to perform all the functions that cell-based tools do.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In some cases, the structured ASIC vendor requires customized tools for their device (e.g., custom physical synthesis) be used, also allowing for the design to be brought into manufacturing more quickly.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Cell libraries of logical primitives are usually provided by the device manufacturer as part of the service.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Although they will incur no additional cost, their release will be covered by the terms of a non-disclosure agreement (NDA) and they will be regarded as intellectual property by the manufacturer.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Usually, their physical design will be pre-defined so they could be termed "hard macros".
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] What most engineers understand as "intellectual property" are IP cores, designs purchased from a third-party as sub-components of a larger ASIC.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] They may be provided in the form of a hardware description language (often termed a "soft macro"), or as a fully routed design that could be printed directly onto an ASIC's mask (often termed a "hard macro").
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Many organizations now sell such pre-designed cores – CPUs, Ethernet, USB or telephone interfaces – and larger organizations may have an entire department or division to produce cores for the rest of the organization.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The company ARM *only* sells IP cores, making it a fabless manufacturer.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Additionally, open-source hardware organizations such as OpenCores are collecting free IP cores, paralleling the open-source software movement in hardware design.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Soft macros are often process-independent (i.e. they can be fabricated on a wide range of manufacturing processes and different manufacturers).
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Hard macros are process-limited and usually further design effort must be invested to migrate (port) to a different process or manufacturer.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Some manufacturers and IC design houses offer multi-project wafer service (MPW) as a method of obtaining low cost prototypes.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Often called shuttles, these MPWs, containing several designs, run at regular, scheduled intervals on a "cut and go" basis, usually with limited liability on the part of the manufacturer.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The contract involves delivery of bare dies or the assembly and packaging of a handful of devices.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The service usually involves the supply of a physical design database (i.e. masking information or pattern generation (PG) tape).
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The manufacturer is often referred to as a "silicon foundry" due to the low involvement it has in the process.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] An **application-specific standard product** (**ASSP**) is an integrated circuit that implements a specific function that appeals to a wide market.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] As opposed to ASICs that combine a collection of functions and are designed by or for one customer, ASSPs are available as off-the-shelf components.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] ASSPs are used in all industries, from automotive to communications.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] For example, two ICs that might or might not be considered ASICs are a controller chip for a PC and a chip for a modem.
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Both of these examples are specific to an application (which is typical of an ASIC) but are sold to many different system vendors (which is typical of standard parts).
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] ASICs such as these are sometimes called application-specific standard products (ASSPs).
[src:do-254/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Examples of ASSPs are encoding/decoding chip, Ethernet network interface controller chip and flash memory controller chip.
[src:do-254/avionics] The term "avionics" was coined in 1949 by Philip J.
[src:do-254/avionics] Klass, senior editor at *Aviation Week & Space Technology* magazine as a portmanteau of "**aviation electronics**".
[src:do-254/avionics] Radio communication was first used in aircraft just prior to World War I.
[src:do-254/avionics] The first airborne radios were in zeppelins, but the military sparked development of light radio sets that could be carried by heavier-than-air craft, so that aerial reconnaissance biplanes could report their observations immediately in case they were shot down.
[src:do-254/avionics] The first experimental radio transmission from an airplane was conducted by the U.S.
[src:do-254/avionics] The first aircraft radios transmitted by radiotelegraphy.
[src:do-254/avionics] They required a two-seat aircraft with a second crewman who operated a telegraph key to spell out messages in Morse code.
[src:do-254/avionics] During World War I, amplitude modulation voice two way radio sets were made possible in 1917 (see TM (triode)) by the development of the triode vacuum tube, which were simple enough that the pilot in a single seat aircraft could use it while flying.
[src:do-254/avionics] Radar, the central technology used today in aircraft navigation and air traffic control, was developed by several nations, mainly in secret, as an air defense system in the 1930s during the runup to World War II.
[src:do-254/avionics] Many modern avionics have their origins in World War II wartime developments.
[src:do-254/avionics] For example, autopilot systems that are commonplace today began as specialized systems to help bomber planes fly steadily enough to hit precision targets from high altitudes.
[src:do-254/avionics] Britain's 1940 decision to share its radar technology with its U.S. ally, particularly the magnetron vacuum tube, in the famous Tizard Mission, significantly shortened the war.
[src:do-254/avionics] Modern avionics is a substantial portion of military aircraft spending.
[src:do-254/avionics] Aircraft like the F-15E and the now retired F-14 have roughly 20 percent of their budget spent on avionics.
[src:do-254/avionics] Most modern helicopters now have budget splits of 60/40 in favour of avionics.
[src:do-254/avionics] The civilian market has also seen a growth in cost of avionics.
[src:do-254/avionics] Flight control systems (fly-by-wire) and new navigation needs brought on by tighter airspaces, have pushed up development costs.
[src:do-254/avionics] The major change has been the recent boom in consumer flying.
[src:do-254/avionics] As more people begin to use planes as their primary method of transportation, more elaborate methods of controlling aircraft safely in these high restrictive airspaces have been invented.
[src:do-254/avionics] Avionics plays a heavy role in modernization initiatives like the Federal Aviation Administration's (FAA) Next Generation Air Transportation System project in the United States and the Single European Sky ATM Research (SESAR) initiative in Europe.
[src:do-254/avionics] The cockpit or, in larger aircraft, under the cockpit of an aircraft or in a movable nosecone, is a typical location for avionic bay equipment, including control, monitoring, communication, navigation, weather, and anti-collision systems.
[src:do-254/avionics] The majority of aircraft power their avionics using 14- or 28‑volt DC electrical systems; however, larger, more sophisticated aircraft (such as airliners or military combat aircraft) have AC systems operating at 115 volts 400 Hz, AC.
[src:do-254/avionics] International standards for avionics equipment are prepared by the Airlines Electronic Engineering Committee and published by ARINC.
[src:do-254/avionics] Communications connect the flight deck to the ground and the flight deck to the passengers.
[src:do-254/avionics] On‑board communications are provided by public-address systems and aircraft intercoms.
[src:do-254/avionics] The VHF aviation communication system works on the airband of 118.000 MHz to 136.975 MHz.
[src:do-254/avionics] Each channel is spaced from the adjacent ones by 8.33 kHz in Europe, 25 kHz elsewhere.
[src:do-254/avionics] VHF is also used for line of sight communication such as aircraft-to-aircraft and aircraft-to-ATC.
[src:do-254/avionics] Amplitude modulation is used, and the conversation is performed in simplex mode.
[src:do-254/avionics] Aircraft communication can also take place using HF (especially for trans-oceanic flights) or satellite communication.
[src:do-254/avionics] Air navigation is the determination of position and direction on or above the surface of the Earth.
[src:do-254/avionics] Avionics can use satellite navigation systems (such as GPS, WAAS, EGNOS and GBAS/LAAS), inertial navigation system (INS), ground-based radio navigation systems (such as VOR or LORAN), or any combination thereof.
[src:do-254/avionics] Some navigation systems such as GPS calculate the position automatically and display it to the flight crew on moving map displays.
[src:do-254/avionics] Older ground-based Navigation systems such as VOR or LORAN requires a pilot or navigator to plot the intersection of signals on a paper map to determine an aircraft's location; modern systems calculate the position automatically and display it to the flight crew on moving map displays.
[src:do-254/avionics] The first hints of glass cockpits emerged in the 1970s when flight-worthy cathode ray tube (CRT) screens began to replace electromechanical displays, gauges and instruments.
[src:do-254/avionics] A "glass" cockpit refers to the use of computer monitors instead of gauges and other analog displays.
[src:do-254/avionics] Aircraft were getting progressively more displays, dials and information dashboards that eventually competed for space and pilot attention.
[src:do-254/avionics] In the 1970s, the average aircraft had more than 100 cockpit instruments and controls.
[src:do-254/avionics] Glass cockpits started to come into being with the Gulfstream G‑IV private jet in 1985.
[src:do-254/avionics] One of the key challenges in glass cockpits is to balance how much control is automated and how much the pilot should do manually.
[src:do-254/avionics] Generally they try to automate flight operations while keeping the pilot constantly informed.
[src:do-254/avionics] Aircraft have means of automatically controlling flight.
[src:do-254/avionics] Autopilot was first invented by Lawrence Sperry during World War I to fly bomber planes steady enough to hit accurate targets from 25,000 feet.
[src:do-254/avionics] When it was first adopted by the U.S. military, a Honeywell engineer sat in the back seat with bolt cutters to disconnect the autopilot in case of emergency.
[src:do-254/avionics] Nowadays most commercial planes are equipped with aircraft flight control systems in order to reduce pilot error and workload at landing or takeoff.
[src:do-254/avionics] The first simple commercial auto-pilots were used to control heading and altitude and had limited authority on things like thrust and flight control surfaces.
[src:do-254/avionics] In helicopters, auto-stabilization was used in a similar way.
[src:do-254/avionics] The first systems were electromechanical.
[src:do-254/avionics] The advent of fly-by-wire and electro-actuated flight surfaces (rather than the traditional hydraulic) has increased safety.
[src:do-254/avionics] As with displays and instruments, critical devices that were electro-mechanical had a finite life.
[src:do-254/avionics] With safety critical systems, the software is very strictly tested.
[src:do-254/avionics] Fuel Quantity Indication System (FQIS) monitors the amount of fuel aboard.
[src:do-254/avionics] Using various sensors, such as capacitance tubes, temperature sensors, densitometers & level sensors, the FQIS computer calculates the mass of fuel remaining on board.
[src:do-254/avionics] Fuel Control and Monitoring System (FCMS) reports fuel remaining on board in a similar manner, but, by controlling pumps & valves, also manages fuel transfers around various tanks.
[src:do-254/avionics] To supplement air traffic control, most large transport aircraft and many smaller ones use a traffic alert and collision avoidance system (TCAS), which can detect the location of nearby aircraft, and provide instructions for avoiding a midair collision.
[src:do-254/avionics] Smaller aircraft may use simpler traffic alerting systems such as TPAS, which are passive (they do not actively interrogate the transponders of other aircraft) and do not provide advisories for conflict resolution.
[src:do-254/avionics] To help avoid controlled flight into terrain (CFIT), aircraft use systems such as ground-proximity warning systems (GPWS), which use radar altimeters as a key element.
[src:do-254/avionics] One of the major weaknesses of GPWS is the lack of "look-ahead" information, because it only provides altitude above terrain "look-down".
[src:do-254/avionics] In order to overcome this weakness, modern aircraft use a terrain awareness warning system (TAWS).
[src:do-254/avionics] Commercial aircraft cockpit data recorders, commonly known as "black boxes", store flight information and audio from the cockpit.
[src:do-254/avionics] They are often recovered from an aircraft after a crash to determine control settings and other parameters during the incident.
[src:do-254/avionics] Weather systems such as weather radar (typically Arinc 708 on commercial aircraft) and lightning detectors are important for aircraft flying at night or in instrument meteorological conditions, where it is not possible for pilots to see the weather ahead.
[src:do-254/avionics] Heavy precipitation (as sensed by radar) or severe turbulence (as sensed by lightning activity) are both indications of strong convective activity and severe turbulence, and weather systems allow pilots to deviate around these areas.
[src:do-254/avionics] Lightning detectors like the Stormscope or Strikefinder have become inexpensive enough that they are practical for light aircraft.
[src:do-254/avionics] In addition to radar and lightning detection, observations and extended radar pictures (such as NEXRAD) are now available through satellite data connections, allowing pilots to see weather conditions far beyond the range of their own in-flight systems.
[src:do-254/avionics] Modern displays allow weather information to be integrated with moving maps, terrain, and traffic onto a single screen, greatly simplifying navigation.
[src:do-254/avionics] Modern weather systems also include wind shear and turbulence detection and terrain and traffic warning systems.
[src:do-254/avionics] In‑plane weather avionics are especially popular in Africa, India, and other countries where air-travel is a growing market, but ground support is not as well developed.
[src:do-254/avionics] There has been a progression towards centralized control of the multiple complex systems fitted to aircraft, including engine monitoring and management.
[src:do-254/avionics] Health and usage monitoring systems (HUMS) are integrated with aircraft management computers to give maintainers early warnings of parts that will need replacement.
[src:do-254/avionics] The integrated modular avionics concept proposes an integrated architecture with application software portable across an assembly of common hardware modules.
[src:do-254/avionics] It has been used in fourth generation jet fighters and the latest generation of airliners.
[src:do-254/avionics] Military aircraft have been designed either to deliver a weapon or to be the eyes and ears of other weapon systems.
[src:do-254/avionics] The vast array of sensors available to the military is used for whatever tactical means required.
[src:do-254/avionics] As with aircraft management, the bigger sensor platforms (like the E‑3D, JSTARS, ASTOR, Nimrod MRA4, Merlin HM Mk 1) have mission-management computers.
[src:do-254/avionics] Police and EMS aircraft also carry sophisticated tactical sensors.
[src:do-254/avionics] While aircraft communications provide the backbone for safe flight, the tactical systems are designed to withstand the rigors of the battlefield.
[src:do-254/avionics] UHF, VHF Tactical (30–88 MHz) and SatCom systems combined with ECCM methods, and cryptography secure the communications.
[src:do-254/avionics] Data links such as Link 11, 16, 22 and BOWMAN, JTRS and even TETRA provide the means of transmitting data (such as images, targeting information etc.).
[src:do-254/avionics] Airborne radar was one of the first tactical sensors.
[src:do-254/avionics] The benefit of altitude providing range has meant a significant focus on airborne radar technologies.
[src:do-254/avionics] Radars include airborne early warning, anti-submarine warfare, and even weather radar (Arinc 708) and ground tracking/proximity radar.
[src:do-254/avionics] The military uses radar in fast jets to help pilots fly at low levels.
[src:do-254/avionics] While the civil market has had weather radar for a while, there are strict rules about using it to navigate the aircraft.
[src:do-254/avionics] Dipping sonar fitted to a range of military helicopters allows the helicopter to protect shipping assets from submarines or surface threats.
[src:do-254/avionics] Maritime support aircraft can drop active and passive sonar devices (sonobuoys) and these are also used to determine the location of enemy submarines.
[src:do-254/avionics] Electro-optic systems include devices such as the head-up display (HUD), forward looking infrared (FLIR), infrared search and track and other passive infrared devices (Passive infrared sensor).
[src:do-254/avionics] These are all used to provide imagery and information to the flight crew.
[src:do-254/avionics] This imagery is used for everything from search and rescue to navigational aids and target acquisition.
[src:do-254/avionics] Electronic support measures and defensive aids systems are used extensively to gather information about threats or possible threats.
[src:do-254/avionics] They can be used to launch devices (in some cases automatically) to counter direct threats against the aircraft.
[src:do-254/avionics] They are also used to determine the state of a threat and identify it.
[src:do-254/avionics] The avionics systems in military, commercial and advanced models of civilian aircraft are interconnected using an avionics databus.
[src:do-254/do-254] The document classifies electronic hardware items into simple or complex categories.
[src:do-254/do-254] The body of DO-254/ED-80 establishes objectives and activities for the systematic design assurance of complex electronic hardware, generally presumed to be *complex* custom micro-coded components, as listed above.
[src:do-254/do-254] However, simple electronic hardware is within the scope of DO-254/ED-80 and applicants propose and use the guidance in this standard to obtain certification approval of simple custom micro-coded components, especially devices that support higher level (A/B) aircraft functions.
[src:do-254/do-254] The DO-254/ED-80 standard is the counterpart to the well-established software standard RTCA DO-178C/EUROCAE ED-12C.
[src:do-254/do-254] With DO-254/ED-80, the certification authorities have indicated that avionics equipment contains both hardware and software, and each is critical to safe operation of aircraft.
[src:do-254/do-254] There are five levels of compliance, A through E, which depend on the effect a failure of the hardware will have on the operation of the aircraft.
[src:do-254/do-254] Level A is the most stringent, defined as "catastrophic" effect (e.g., loss of the aircraft), while a failure of Level E hardware will not affect the safety of the aircraft.
[src:do-254/do-254] Meeting Level A compliance for complex electronic hardware requires a much higher level of verification and validation than Level E compliance.
[src:do-254/do-254] The main regulations that must be followed are the capturing and tracking of requirements throughout the design and verification process.
[src:do-254/do-254] The hardware design and hardware verification need to be done independently.
[src:do-254/do-254] The hardware designer works to ensure the design of the hardware will meet the defined requirements.
[src:do-254/do-254] Meanwhile, the verification engineer will generate a verification plan which will allow for testing the hardware to verify that it meets all of its derived requirements.
[src:do-254/do-254] The planning process is the first step where the design authority (the company who develops the H/W and implements the COTS into its design) declares its approach towards the certification.
[src:do-254/do-254] At this point the PHAC (Plan for H/W Aspects of Certification) is presented to the authorities (EASA, FAA...).
[src:do-254/do-254] In this plan, the developer presents its approach and how DO-254/ED-80 is implemented.
[src:do-254/do-254] The PHAC is submitted as part of the authorities 1st stage of involvement (SOI#1).
[src:do-254/do-254] For a generic DO-254 based process, a job aid is provided including the Stages of Involvement (SOIs) defined by FAA on the "Airborne Electronic Hardware Review Job Aid".
[src:do-254/do-254] The hardware requirement validation process provides assurance that the hardware item derived requirements are correct and complete with respect to system requirements allocated to the hardware item.
[src:do-254/do-254] Validation of hardware requirements allocated from system requirements is a system process, rather than a hardware process.
[src:do-254/do-254] As such, hardware requirements that are derived by hardware processes should be identified to system processes for validation against the system requirements.
[src:do-254/do-254] The verification process provides assurance that the hardware item implementation meets all of the hardware requirements, including derived requirements.
[src:do-254/do-254] Methods of verification include qualitative review, quantitative analysis, and functional testing.
[src:do-254/do-254] While simple electronic hardware (SEH) is within the scope of DO-254/ED-80, its guidance on the subject has been considered inadequate among applicants seeking certification of simple electronic hardware.
[src:do-254/do-254] The Certification Authorities Software Team published the Position Paper CAST-30, *Simple Electronic Hardware and RTCA Document DO-254 and EUROCAE Document ED-80*, to provide clarification to the guidance for simple electronic hardware.
[src:do-254/do-254] This clarification was amplified as FAA guidance in FAA Order 8110.105.
[src:do-254/do-254] Essentially, for simple electronic hardware, the verification through “comprehensive combination of deterministic testing and analysis” that justifies the simple classification needs to be defined, performed, and recorded.
[src:do-254/do-254] However, the appropriate "rigor and thoroughness" of that verification depends on the hardware design assurance level.
[src:do-254/do-254] If certification as a simple electronic device is sought, minimal documentation still should be submitted.
[src:do-254/do-254] A Plan for Hardware Aspects of Certification (PHAC) should be submitted to communicate the justification and means of certification, and a Hardware Verification Plan should be submitted to communicate the rigor and methods of the deterministic testing and analysis.
[src:do-254/do-254] Hardware Accomplishment Summary should be submitted to show compliance to the PHAC, and a Hardware Configuration Index should be submitted to define the production baseline that is the subject of the Hardware Identification and Compliance Statement in the Hardware Accomplishment Summary.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] A **field-programmable gate array** (**FPGA**) is a type of configurable integrated circuit that can be repeatedly programmed after manufacturing.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGAs are a subset of logic devices referred to as programmable logic devices (PLDs).
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] They consist of a grid-connected array of programmable logic blocks that can be configured "in the field" to interconnect with other logic blocks to perform various digital functions.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGAs are often used in limited (low) quantity production of custom-made products, and in research and development, where the higher cost of individual FPGAs is not as important and where creating and manufacturing a custom circuit would not be feasible.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Other applications for FPGAs include the telecommunications, automotive, aerospace, and industrial sectors, which benefit from their flexibility, high signal processing speed, and parallel processing abilities.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] An FPGA configuration is generally written using a hardware description language (HDL), e.g., VHDL, similar to the ones used for application-specific integrated circuits (ASICs).
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Circuit diagrams were formerly used to write the configuration.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] The logic blocks of an FPGA can be configured to perform complex combinational functions, or act as simple logic gates like AND and XOR.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] In most FPGAs, logic blocks also include memory elements, which may be simple flip-flops or more sophisticated blocks of memory.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Many FPGAs can be reprogrammed to implement different logic functions, allowing flexible reconfigurable computing as performed in computer software.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGAs are also commonly used during the development of ASICs to speed up the simulation process.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] The FPGA industry sprouted from programmable read-only memory (PROM) and programmable logic devices (PLDs).
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] PROMs and PLDs both had the option of being programmed in batches in a factory or in the field (field-programmable).
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Altera was founded in 1983 and delivered the industry's first reprogrammable logic device in 1984 – the EP300 – which featured a quartz window in the package that allowed users to shine an ultraviolet lamp on the die to erase the EPROM cells that held the device configuration.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Xilinx (now owned by AMD) produced the first commercially viable field-programmable gate array in 1985 – the XC2064.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] The XC2064 had programmable gates and programmable interconnects between gates, the beginnings of a new technology and market.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] The XC2064 had 64 configurable logic blocks (CLBs), with two three-input lookup tables (LUTs).
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] In 1987, the Naval Surface Warfare Center funded an experiment proposed by Steve Casselman to develop a computer that would implement 600,000 reprogrammable gates.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Casselman was successful and a patent related to the system was issued in 1992.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Altera and Xilinx continued unchallenged and quickly grew from 1985 to the mid-1990s when competitors sprouted up, eroding a significant portion of their market share.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] By 1993, Actel (later Microsemi, now Microchip) was serving about 18 percent of the market.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] The 1990s were a period of rapid growth for FPGAs, both in circuit sophistication and the volume of production.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] In the early 1990s, FPGAs were primarily used in telecommunications and networking.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] By the end of the decade, FPGAs found their way into consumer, automotive, and industrial applications.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] By 2013, Altera (31 percent), Xilinx (36 percent), and Actel (10 percent) together represented approximately 77 percent of the FPGA market.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Companies like Microsoft have started to use FPGAs to accelerate high-performance, computationally intensive systems (like the data centers that operate their Bing search engine), due to the performance per watt advantage FPGAs deliver.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Microsoft began using FPGAs to accelerate Bing in 2014, and in 2018 began deploying FPGAs across other data center workloads for their Azure cloud computing platform.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Since 2019, modern generations of FPGAs have been integrated with other architectures like AI engines to target workloads in the artificial intelligence domain.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] The following timelines indicate progress in different aspects of FPGA design.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] A *design start* is a new custom design for implementation on an FPGA.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Contemporary FPGAs have ample logic gates and RAM blocks to implement complex digital computations.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGAs can be used to implement any logical function that an ASIC can perform.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] The ability to update the functionality after shipping, partial re-configuration of a portion of the design and the low non-recurring engineering costs relative to an ASIC design (notwithstanding the generally higher unit cost), offer advantages for many applications.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] As FPGA designs employ very fast I/O rates and bidirectional data buses, it becomes a challenge to verify correct timing of valid data within setup time and hold time.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Floor planning helps resource allocation within FPGAs to meet these timing constraints.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Some FPGAs have analog features in addition to digital functions.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] The most common analog feature is a programmable slew rate on each output pin.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] This allows the user to set low rates on lightly loaded pins that would otherwise ring or couple unacceptably, and to set higher rates on heavily loaded high-speed channels that would otherwise run too slowly.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Also common are quartz-crystal oscillator driver circuitry, on-chip RC oscillators, and phase-locked loops with embedded voltage-controlled oscillators used for clock generation and management as well as for high-speed serializer and deserializer (SERDES) transmit clocks and receiver clock recovery.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Fairly common are differential comparators on input pins designed to be connected to differential signaling channels.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] A few mixed-signal FPGAs have integrated peripheral analog-to-digital converters (ADCs) and digital-to-analog converters (DACs) with analog signal conditioning blocks, allowing them to operate as a system on a chip (SoC).
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Such devices blur the line between an FPGA, which carries digital ones and zeros on its internal programmable interconnect fabric, and field-programmable analog array (FPAA), which carries analog values on its internal programmable interconnect fabric.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] The most common FPGA architecture consists of an array of logic blocks called configurable logic blocks (CLBs) or logic array blocks (LABs) (depending on vendor), I/O pads, and routing channels.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Generally, all the routing channels have the same width (number of signals).
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Multiple I/O pads may fit into the height of one row or the width of one column in the array.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] "An application circuit must be mapped into an FPGA with adequate resources.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] While the number of logic blocks and I/Os required is easily determined from the design, the number of routing channels needed may vary considerably even among designs with the same amount of logic.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] For example, a crossbar switch requires much more routing than a systolic array with the same gate count.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Since unused routing channels increase the cost (and decrease the performance) of the FPGA without providing any benefit, FPGA manufacturers try to provide just enough channels so that most designs that will fit in terms of lookup tables (LUTs) and I/Os can be routed.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] In general, a logic block consists of a few logical cells.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] A typical cell consists of a 4-input LUT, a full adder (FA) and a D-type flip-flop.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] The LUT might be split into two 3-input LUTs.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] In *normal mode* those are combined into a 4-input LUT through the first multiplexer (mux).
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] In *arithmetic* mode, their outputs are fed to the adder.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] The selection of mode is programmed into the second mux.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] The output can be either synchronous or asynchronous, depending on the programming of the third mux.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] In practice, the entire adder or parts of it are stored as functions into the LUTs in order to save space.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Modern FPGA families expand upon the above capabilities to include higher-level functionality fixed in silicon.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Having these common functions embedded in the circuit reduces the area required and gives those functions increased performance compared to building them from logical primitives.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Examples of these include multipliers, generic DSP blocks, embedded processors, high-speed I/O logic and embedded memories.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Higher-end FPGAs can contain high-speed multi-gigabit transceivers and *hard IP cores* such as processor cores, Ethernet medium access control units, PCI or PCI Express controllers, and external memory controllers.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] These cores exist alongside the programmable fabric, but they are built out of transistors instead of LUTs so they have ASIC-level performance and power consumption without consuming a significant amount of fabric resources, leaving more of the fabric free for the application-specific logic.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] The multi-gigabit transceivers also contain high-performance signal conditioning circuitry along with high-speed serializers and deserializers, components that cannot be built out of LUTs.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Higher-level physical layer (PHY) functionality such as line coding may or may not be implemented alongside the serializers and deserializers in hard logic, depending on the FPGA.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] An alternate approach to using hard macro processors is to make use of soft processor IP cores that are implemented within the FPGA logic.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Nios II, MicroBlaze and Mico32 are examples of popular softcore processors.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Many modern FPGAs are programmed at *run time*, which has led to the idea of reconfigurable computing or reconfigurable systems – CPUs that reconfigure themselves to suit the task at hand.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Additionally, new non-FPGA architectures are beginning to emerge.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Software-configurable microprocessors such as the Stretch S5000 adopt a hybrid approach by providing an array of processor cores and FPGA-like programmable cores on the same chip.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] In 2012 the coarse-grained architectural approach was taken a step further by combining the logic blocks and interconnects of traditional FPGAs with embedded microprocessors and related peripherals to form a complete system on a programmable chip.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Examples of such hybrid technologies can be found in the Xilinx Zynq-7000 all programmable SoC, which includes a 1.0 GHz dual-core ARM Cortex-A9 MPCore processor embedded within the FPGA's logic fabric, or in the Altera Arria V FPGA, which includes an 800 MHz dual-core ARM Cortex-A9 MPCore.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] The Atmel FPSLIC is another such device, which uses an AVR processor in combination with Atmel's programmable logic architecture.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] The Microsemi SmartFusion devices incorporate an ARM Cortex-M3 hard processor core (with up to 512 kB of flash and 64 kB of RAM) and analog peripherals such as a multi-channel analog-to-digital converters and digital-to-analog converters in their flash memory-based FPGA fabric.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Most of the logic inside of an FPGA is synchronous circuitry that requires a clock signal.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGAs contain dedicated global and regional routing networks for clock and reset, typically implemented as an H tree, so they can be delivered with minimal skew.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGAs may contain analog phase-locked loop or delay-locked loop components to synthesize new clock frequencies and manage jitter.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Complex designs can use multiple clocks with different frequency and phase relationships, each forming separate clock domains.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] These clock signals can be generated locally by an oscillator or they can be recovered from a data stream.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Care must be taken when building clock domain crossing circuitry to avoid metastability.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Some FPGAs contain dual port RAM blocks that are capable of working with different clocks, aiding in the construction of building FIFOs and dual port buffers that bridge clock domains.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] To shrink the size and power consumption of FPGAs, vendors such as Tabula and Xilinx have introduced 3D or stacked architectures.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Following the introduction of its 28 nm 7-series FPGAs, Xilinx said that several of the highest-density parts in those FPGA product lines will be constructed using multiple dies in one package, employing technology developed for 3D construction and stacked-die assemblies.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Xilinx's approach stacks several (three or four) active FPGA dies side by side on a silicon interposer – a single piece of silicon that carries passive interconnect.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] The multi-die construction also allows different parts of the FPGA to be created with different process technologies, as the process requirements are different between the FPGA fabric itself and the very high speed 28 Gbit/s serial transceivers.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] An FPGA built in this way is called a *heterogeneous FPGA*.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Altera's heterogeneous approach involves using a single monolithic FPGA die and connecting other dies and technologies to the FPGA using Intel's embedded multi-die interconnect bridge (EMIB) technology.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] To define the behavior of the FPGA, the user provides a design in a hardware description language (HDL) or as a schematic design.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] The HDL form is more suited to work with large structures because it's possible to specify high-level functional behavior rather than drawing every piece by hand.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] However, schematic entry can allow for easier visualization of a design and its component modules.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Using an electronic design automation tool, a technology-mapped netlist is generated.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] The netlist can then be fit to the actual FPGA architecture using a process called *place and route*, usually performed by the FPGA company's proprietary place-and-route software.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] The user will validate the results using timing analysis, simulation, and other verification and validation techniques.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Once the design and validation process is complete, the binary file generated, typically using the FPGA vendor's proprietary software, is used to (re-)configure the FPGA.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] This file is transferred to the FPGA via a serial interface (JTAG) or to an external memory device such as an EEPROM.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] The most common HDLs are VHDL and Verilog.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] National Instruments' LabVIEW graphical programming language (sometimes referred to as *G*) has an FPGA add-in module available to target and program FPGA hardware.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Verilog was created to simplify the process, making HDL more robust and flexible.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Verilog has a C-like syntax, unlike VHDL which is based on Ada.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] To simplify the design of complex systems in FPGAs, there exist libraries of predefined complex functions and circuits that have been tested and optimized to speed up the design process.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] These predefined circuits are commonly called *intellectual property (IP) cores*, and are available from FPGA vendors and third-party IP suppliers.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] They are rarely free, and typically released under proprietary licenses.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Other predefined circuits are available from developer communities such as OpenCores (typically released under free and open source licenses such as the GPL, BSD or similar license).
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Such designs are known as open-source hardware.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] In a typical design flow, an FPGA application developer will simulate the design at multiple stages throughout the design process.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Initially, the RTL description in VHDL or Verilog is simulated by creating test benches to simulate the system and observe results.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Then, after the synthesis engine has mapped the design to a netlist, the netlist is translated to a gate-level description where simulation is repeated to confirm the synthesis proceeded without errors.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Finally, the design is laid out in the FPGA at which point propagation delay values can be back-annotated onto the netlist, and the simulation can be run again with these values.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] More recently, OpenCL (Open Computing Language) is being used by programmers to take advantage of the performance and power efficiencies that FPGAs provide.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] OpenCL allows programmers to develop code in the C programming language.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] For further information, see high-level synthesis and C to HDL.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Most FPGAs rely on an SRAM-based approach to be programmed.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] These FPGAs are in-system programmable and re-programmable, but require external boot devices.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] For example, flash memory or EEPROM devices may load contents into internal SRAM that controls routing and logic.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] In 2016, long-time industry rivals Xilinx (now part of AMD) and Altera were the FPGA market leaders.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] At that time, they controlled nearly 90 percent of the market.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Both Xilinx and Altera provide proprietary electronic design automation software for Windows and Linux (ISE/Vivado and Quartus) which enables engineers to design, analyze, simulate, and synthesize (compile) their designs.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] In March 2010, Tabula announced their FPGA technology that uses time-multiplexed logic and interconnect that claims potential cost savings for high-density applications.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] On March 24, 2015, Tabula officially shut down.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] On June 1, 2015, Intel announced it would acquire Altera for approximately US$16.7 billion and completed the acquisition on December 30, 2015.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] On October 27, 2020, AMD announced it would acquire Xilinx and completed the acquisition valued at about US$50 billion in February 2022.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] In February 2024 Altera became independent of Intel again.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] An FPGA can be used to solve any problem that is computable.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGAs can be used to implement a soft microprocessor, such as the Xilinx MicroBlaze or Altera Nios II.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] But their advantage lies in that they are significantly faster for some applications because of their parallel nature and optimality in terms of the number of gates used for certain processes.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGAs were originally introduced as competitors to complex programmable logic devices (CPLDs) to implement glue logic for printed circuit boards.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] As their size, capabilities, and speed increased, FPGAs took over additional functions to the point where some are now marketed as full systems on chips (SoCs).
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Particularly with the introduction of dedicated multipliers into FPGA architectures in the late 1990s, applications that had traditionally been the sole reserve of digital signal processors (DSPs) began to use FPGAs instead.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] The evolution of FPGAs has motivated an increase in the use of these devices, whose architecture allows the development of hardware solutions optimized for complex tasks, such as 3D MRI image segmentation, 3D discrete wavelet transform, tomographic image reconstruction, or PET/MRI systems.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] The developed solutions can perform intensive computation tasks with parallel processing, are dynamically reprogrammable, and have a low cost, all while meeting the hard real-time requirements associated with medical imaging.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Another trend in the use of FPGAs is hardware acceleration, where one can use the FPGA to accelerate certain parts of an algorithm and share part of the computation between the FPGA and a general-purpose processor.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] The search engine Bing is noted for adopting FPGA acceleration for its search algorithm in 2014.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] As of 2018, FPGAs are seeing increased use as AI accelerators including Microsoft's Project Catapult and for accelerating artificial neural networks for machine learning applications.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Originally, FPGAs were reserved for specific vertical applications where the volume of production is small.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] For these low-volume applications, the premium that companies pay in hardware cost per unit for a programmable chip is more affordable than the development resources spent on creating an ASIC.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Often a custom-made chip would be cheaper if made in larger quantities, but FPGAs may be chosen to quickly bring a product to market.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] By 2017, new cost and performance dynamics broadened the range of viable applications.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGAs play a crucial role in modern military communications, especially in systems like the Joint Tactical Radio System (JTRS) and in devices from companies such as Thales and Harris Corporation.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Their flexibility and programmability make them ideal for military communications, offering customizable and secure signal processing.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] In the JTRS, used by the US military, FPGAs provide adaptability and real-time processing, crucial for meeting various communication standards and encryption methods.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Concerning hardware security, FPGAs have both advantages and disadvantages as compared to ASICs or secure microprocessors.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGAs' flexibility makes malicious modifications during fabrication a lower risk.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Previously, for many FPGAs, the design bitstream was exposed while the FPGA loads it from external memory, typically during powerup.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] All major FPGA vendors now offer a spectrum of security solutions to designers, such as bitstream encryption and authentication.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] For example, Altera and Xilinx offer AES encryption (up to 256-bit) for bitstreams stored in an external flash memory.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Physical unclonable functions (PUFs) are integrated circuits that have their own unique signatures and can be used to secure FPGAs while taking up very little hardware space.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGAs that store their configuration internally in nonvolatile flash memory, such as Microsemi's ProAsic 3 or Lattice's XP2 programmable devices, do not expose the bitstream and do not need encryption.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Customers wanting a higher guarantee of tamper resistance can use write-once, antifuse FPGAs from vendors such as Microsemi.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] With its Stratix 10 FPGAs and SoCs, Altera introduced a Secure Device Manager and physical unclonable functions to provide high levels of protection against physical attacks.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] In 2012, researchers Sergei Skorobogatov and Christopher Woods demonstrated that some FPGAs can be vulnerable to hostile intent.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] In 2020, a critical vulnerability (named Starbleed) was discovered in all Xilinx 7 series FPGAs that rendered bitstream encryption useless.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Xilinx did not produce a hardware revision.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Ultrascale and later devices, already on the market at the time, were not affected.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Historically, FPGAs have been slower, less energy efficient and generally achieved less functionality than their fixed ASIC counterparts.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] A study from 2006 showed that designs implemented on FPGAs need on average 40 times as much area, draw 12 times as much dynamic power, and run at one third the speed of corresponding ASIC implementations.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Advantages of FPGAs include the ability to reprogram equipment in the field to fix bugs or make other improvements.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Some FPGAs have the capability of partial re-configuration that lets one portion of the device be re-programmed while other portions continue running.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Other advantages may include shorter time to market and lower non-recurring engineering costs.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Vendors can also take a middle road via FPGA prototyping: developing their prototype hardware on FPGAs, but manufacturing their final version as an ASIC after the design has been committed.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] This is often also the case with new processor designs.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] The primary differences between CPLDs and FPGAs are architectural.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] A CPLD has a comparatively restrictive structure consisting of one or more programmable sum-of-products logic arrays feeding a relatively small number of clocked registers.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] As a result, CPLDs are less flexible but have the advantage of more predictable propagation delay.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGA architectures, on the other hand, are dominated by interconnect.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] This makes them far more flexible but also far more complex to design for, or at least requiring more complex electronic design automation (EDA) software.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Another distinction between FPGAs and CPLDs is one of size, as FPGAs are usually much larger in terms of resources than CPLDs.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Typically only FPGAs contain more complex embedded functions such as adders, multipliers, memory, and serializer/deserializers.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Another common distinction is that CPLDs contain embedded flash memory to store their configuration, while FPGAs typically store their configuration in SRAM and require external non-volatile memory to initialize it on powerup.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] When a design requires simple instant-on, CPLDs are generally preferred.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] Sometimes both CPLDs and FPGAs are used in a single system design.
[src:do-254/field-programmable-gate-array] In those designs, CPLDs generally perform glue logic functions.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] The earliest electronic design automation is attributed to IBM with the documentation of its 700 series computers in the 1950s.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] IBM has developed one of the earliest computer-aided design (CAD) systems, known as Automated Logic Diagram (ALD), which was originally executed on the IBM 704 and 705 mainframe computers.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] The design process started with engineers manually drafting logic schematics, which were later transcribed onto standardized templates and converted into punch cards for digital processing.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] Although focused on mechanical geometry, General Motors’ DAC-1, built jointly with IBM, was among the earliest interactive, graphics-driven CAD systems and proved the practicality of screen-based editing for complex engineering data, an idea adopted by IC layout tools.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] Prior to the development of EDA, integrated circuits were designed by hand and manually laid out.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] Some advanced shops used geometric software to generate tapes for a Gerber photoplotter, responsible for generating a monochromatic exposure image, but even those copied digital recordings of mechanically drawn components.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] The process was fundamentally graphic, with the translation from electronics to graphics done manually; the best-known company from this era was Calma, whose GDSII format is still in use today.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] In the early 1970s, developers started to automate circuit design in addition to drafting and the first placement and routing tools were developed.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] Because of the Cold War, developments often occurred in near parallel.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] In the Western world, the proceedings of the IEEE and the Design Automation Conference catalogued the large majority of the developments of the time, and by 1973 a large bibliography was needed to keep track of developments in the field.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] In the Soviet Union, progress was largely described in a series of books, starting in 1975.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] Calma’s Graphic Design System (GDS, 1971) and its 32-bit successor GDSII (1978) let engineers digitise and edit full-chip layouts on minicomputers; the accompanying GDSII Stream file became the de-facto mask exchange standard and is still recognised in modern design flows.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] The next era began following the publication of "Introduction to VLSI Systems" by Carver Mead and Lynn Conway in 1980, and is considered the standard textbook for chip design.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] The result was an increase in the complexity of the chips that could be designed, with improved access to design verification tools that used logic simulation.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] The chips were easier to lay out and more likely to function correctly, since their designs could be simulated more thoroughly prior to construction.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] Although the languages and tools have evolved, this general approach of specifying the desired behavior in a textual programming language and letting the tools derive the detailed physical design remains the basis of digital IC design today.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] The earliest EDA tools were produced academically.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] One of the most famous was the "Berkeley VLSI Tools Tarball", a set of UNIX utilities used to design early VLSI systems.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] Widely used were the Espresso heuristic logic minimizer, responsible for circuit complexity reductions and Magic, a computer-aided design platform.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] Another crucial development was the formation of MOSIS, a consortium of universities and fabricators that developed an inexpensive way to train student chip designers by producing real integrated circuits.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] The basic concept was to use reliable, low-cost, relatively low-technology IC processes and pack a large number of projects per wafer, with several copies of chips from each project remaining preserved.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] Cooperating fabricators either donated the processed wafers or sold them at cost, as they saw the program as helpful to their own long-term growth.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] 1981 marked the beginning of EDA as an industry.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] For many years, the larger electronic companies, such as Hewlett-Packard, Tektronix and Intel, had pursued EDA internally, with managers and developers beginning to spin out of these companies to concentrate on EDA as a business.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] Daisy Systems, Mentor Graphics and Valid Logic Systems were all founded around this time and collectively referred to as DMV.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] Department of Defense additionally began funding of VHDL as a hardware description language.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] Within a few years, there were many companies specializing in EDA, each with a slightly different emphasis.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] The first trade show for EDA was held at the Design Automation Conference in 1984, and in 1986, Verilog, another popular high-level design language, was first introduced as a hardware description language by Gateway Design Automation.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] Simulators quickly followed these introductions, permitting direct simulation of chip designs and executable specifications.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] Within several years, back-ends were developed to perform logic synthesis.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] Current digital flows are extremely modular, with front ends producing standardized design descriptions that compile into invocations of units similar to cells without regard to their individual technology.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] Cells implement logic or other electronic functions via the utilisation of a particular integrated circuit technology.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] Fabricators generally provide libraries of components for their production processes, with simulation models that fit standard simulation tools.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] Most analog circuits are still designed in a manual fashion, requiring specialist knowledge that is unique to analog design (such as matching concepts).
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] Hence, analog EDA tools are far less modular, since many more functions are required, they interact more strongly and the components are, in general, less ideal.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] EDA for electronics has rapidly increased in importance with the continuous scaling of semiconductor technology.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] Some users are foundry operators, who operate the semiconductor fabrication facilities ("fabs") and additional individuals responsible for utilising the technology design-service companies who use EDA software to evaluate an incoming design for manufacturing readiness.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] EDA tools are also used for programming design functionality into FPGAs or field-programmable gate arrays, customisable integrated circuit designs.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] Synopsys announced a planned acquisition of Ansys in 2024, but Ansys remains an independent, publicly traded company until the deal closes (expected H1 2025).
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] Many EDA companies acquire small companies with software or other technology that can be adapted to their core business.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] This is happening due to a trend to place entire electronic systems on a single chip.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] Machine-learning methods are now applied at every major stage of the integrated-circuit design flow, from high-level synthesis through sign-off.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] Machine-learning shortens turnaround times and improves power, performance and area (PPA).
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] EDA vendors have since integrated similar optimization engines into production toolchains.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] The OpenROAD Project (Foundations and Realisation of Open, Accessible Design), launched under DARPA’s IDEA program, released a no-human-in-the-loop RTL-to-GDS flow that has successfully taped-out designs.
[src:do-254/hardware-verification] Conferences such as ORConf and the annual FOSSi Foundation roadmap sessions now dedicate substantial tracks to open-source EDA progress.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The *reliability function* is theoretically defined as the probability of success.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] In practice, it is calculated using different techniques, and its value ranges between 0 and 1, where 0 indicates no probability of success while 1 indicates definite success.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] This probability is estimated from detailed (physics of failure) analysis, previous data sets, or through reliability testing and reliability modeling.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Availability, testability, maintainability, and maintenance are often defined as a part of "reliability engineering" in reliability programs.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability often plays a vital role in the cost-effectiveness of overall systems.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering deals with the prediction, prevention, and management of high levels of "lifetime" engineering uncertainty and risks of failure.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Although stochastic parameters define and affect reliability, reliability is not only achieved by mathematics and statistics.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering relates closely to quality engineering, safety engineering, and system safety, in that they use common methods for their analysis and may require input from each other.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] It can be said that a system must be reliably safe.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering focuses on the costs of failure caused by the system downtime, cost of spares, repair equipment, personnel, and cost of warranty claims.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The word *reliability* can be traced back to 1816 and is first attested to the poet Samuel Taylor Coleridge.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Before World War II the term was linked mostly to repeatability; a test (in any type of science) was considered "reliable" if the same results would be obtained repeatedly.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] In the 1920s, product improvement through the use of statistical process control was promoted by Dr.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Shewhart at Bell Labs, around the time that Waloddi Weibull was working on statistical models for fatigue.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The development of reliability engineering was here on a parallel path with quality.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The modern use of the word reliability was defined by the U.S. military in the 1940s, characterizing a product that would operate when expected and for a specified period.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] In World War II, many reliability issues stemmed from the inherent unreliability of electronic equipment available at the time and from fatigue.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Miner published a seminal paper titled "Cumulative Damage in Fatigue" in an ASME journal.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] A main application for reliability engineering in the military was for the vacuum tube as used in radar systems and other electronics, for which reliability proved to be very problematic and costly.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The IEEE formed the Reliability Society in 1948.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] In 1950, the United States Department of Defense formed a group called the "Advisory Group on the Reliability of Electronic Equipment" (AGREE) to investigate reliability methods for military equipment.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] In the 1960s, more emphasis was given to reliability testing on component and system levels.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The famous military standard MIL-STD-781 was created at that time.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Around this period also the much-used predecessor to military handbook 217 was published by RCA and was used for the prediction of failure rates of electronic components.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The emphasis on component reliability and empirical research (e.g.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] More pragmatic approaches, as used in the consumer industries, were being used.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] In the 1980s, televisions were increasingly made up of solid-state semiconductors.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Automobiles rapidly increased their use of semiconductors with a variety of microcomputers under the hood and in the dash.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Large air conditioning systems developed electronic controllers, as did microwave ovens and a variety of other appliances.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Communications systems began to adopt electronics to replace older mechanical switching systems.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Bellcore issued the first consumer prediction methodology for telecommunications, and SAE developed a similar document SAE870050 for automotive applications.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The nature of predictions evolved during the decade, and it became apparent that die complexity wasn't the only factor that determined failure rates for integrated circuits (ICs).
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Kam Wong published a paper questioning the bathtub curve—see also reliability-centered maintenance.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] During this decade, the failure rate of many components dropped by a factor of 10.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Software became important to the reliability of systems.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] By the 1990s, the pace of IC development was picking up.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Wider use of stand-alone microcomputers was common, and the PC market helped keep IC densities following Moore's law and doubling about every 18 months.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering was now changing as it moved towards understanding the physics of failure.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Failure rates for components kept dropping, but system-level issues became more prominent.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Systems thinking has become more and more important.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] For software, the CMM model (Capability Maturity Model) was developed, which gave a more qualitative approach to reliability.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] ISO 9000 added reliability measures to the design and development portion of certification.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The expansion of the World Wide Web created new challenges of security and trust.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The older problem of too little reliable information available had now been replaced by too much information of questionable value.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Consumer reliability problems could now be discussed online in real-time using data.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] New technologies such as micro-electromechanical systems (MEMS), handheld GPS, and hand-held devices that combine cell phones and computers all represent challenges to maintaining reliability.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Product development time continued to shorten through this decade and what had been done in three years was being done in 18 months.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] This meant that reliability tools and tasks had to be more closely tied to the development process itself.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] In many ways, reliability has become part of everyday life and consumer expectations.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is the probability of a product performing its intended function under specified operating conditions in a manner that meets or exceeds customer expectations.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] To identify and correct the causes of failures that do occur despite the efforts to prevent them.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] To determine ways of coping with failures that do occur, if their causes have not been corrected.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] To apply methods for estimating the likely reliability of new designs, and for analysing reliability data.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The reason for the priority emphasis is that it is by far the most effective way of working, in terms of minimizing costs and generating reliable products.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The primary skills that are required, therefore, are the ability to understand and anticipate the possible causes of failures, and knowledge of how to prevent them.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] It is also necessary to know the methods that can be used for analyzing designs and data.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering for "complex systems" requires a different, more elaborate systems approach than for non-complex systems.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] These analyses must be done properly and with much attention to detail to be effective.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Consistent with the creation of safety cases, for example per ARP4761, the goal of reliability assessments is to provide a robust set of qualitative and quantitative evidence that the use of a component or system will not be associated with unacceptable risk.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The risk here is the combination of probability and severity of the failure incident (scenario) occurring.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The severity can be looked at from a system safety or a system availability point of view.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability for safety can be thought of as a very different focus from reliability for system availability.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Availability and safety can exist in dynamic tension as keeping a system too available can be unsafe.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Forcing an engineering system into a safe state too quickly can force false alarms that impede the availability of the system.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] In a *de minimis* definition, the severity of failures includes the cost of spare parts, man-hours, logistics, damage (secondary failures), and downtime of machines which may cause production loss.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] What is acceptable is determined by the managing authority or customers or the affected communities.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Residual risk is the risk that is left over after all reliability activities have finished, and includes the unidentified risk—and is therefore not completely quantifiable.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The complexity of the technical systems such as improvements of design and materials, planned inspections, fool-proof design, and backup redundancy decreases risk and increases the cost.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The risk can be decreased to ALARA (as low as reasonably achievable) or ALAPA (as low as practically achievable) levels.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Implementing a reliability program is not simply a software purchase; it is not just a checklist of items that must be completed that ensure one has reliable products and processes.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program is a complex learning and knowledge-based system unique to one's products and processes.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] It is supported by leadership, built on the skills that one develops within a team, integrated into business processes, and executed by following proven standard work practices.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program plan is used to document exactly what "best practices" (tasks, methods, tools, analysis, and tests) are required for a particular (sub)system, as well as clarify customer requirements for reliability assessment.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] For large-scale complex systems, the reliability program plan should be a separate document.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Resource determination for manpower and budgets for testing and other tasks is critical for a successful program.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] In general, the amount of work required for an effective program for complex systems is large.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program plan is essential for achieving high levels of reliability, testability, maintainability, and the resulting system availability, and is developed early during system development and refined over the system's life cycle.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] It specifies not only what the reliability engineer does, but also the tasks performed by other stakeholders.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] An effective reliability program plan must be approved by top program management, which is responsible for the allocation of sufficient resources for its implementation.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program plan may also be used to evaluate and improve the availability of a system by the strategy of focusing on increasing testability & maintainability and not on reliability.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Improving maintainability is generally easier than improving reliability.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Maintainability estimates (repair rates) are also generally more accurate.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] However, because the uncertainties in the reliability estimates are in most cases very large, they are likely to dominate the availability calculation (prediction uncertainty problem), even when maintainability levels are very high.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] When reliability is not under control, more complicated issues may arise, like manpower (maintainers/customer service capability) shortages, spare part availability, logistic delays, lack of repair facilities, extensive retrofit and complex configuration management costs, and others.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The problem of unreliability may be increased also due to the "domino effect" of maintenance-induced failures after repairs.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Focusing only on maintainability is therefore not enough.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] If failures are prevented, none of the other issues are of any importance, and therefore reliability is generally regarded as the most important part of availability.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability needs to be evaluated and improved related to both availability and the total cost of ownership (TCO) due to the cost of spare parts, maintenance man-hours, transport costs, storage costs, part obsolete risks, etc.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] But, as GM and Toyota have belatedly discovered, TCO also includes the downstream liability costs when reliability calculations have not sufficiently or accurately addressed customers' bodily risks.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Often a trade-off is needed between the two.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] There might be a maximum ratio between availability and cost of ownership.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The testability of a system should also be addressed in the plan, as this is the link between reliability and maintainability.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The maintenance strategy can influence the reliability of a system (e.g., by preventive and/or predictive maintenance), although it can never bring it above the inherent reliability.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The reliability plan should clearly provide a strategy for availability control.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Whether only availability or also cost of ownership is more important depends on the use of the system.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] A proper reliability plan should always address RAMT analysis in its total context.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] RAMT stands for reliability, availability, maintainability/maintenance, and testability in the context of the customer's needs.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] For any system, one of the first tasks of reliability engineering is to adequately specify the reliability and maintainability requirements allocated from the overall availability needs and, more importantly, derived from proper design failure analysis or preliminary prototype test results.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Clear requirements (able to be designed to) should constrain the designers from designing particular unreliable items/constructions/interfaces/systems.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Setting only availability, reliability, testability, or maintainability targets (e.g., max. failure rates) is not appropriate.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] This is a broad misunderstanding about Reliability Requirements Engineering.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability requirements address the system itself, including test and assessment requirements, and associated tasks and documentation.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability requirements are included in the appropriate system or subsystem requirements specifications, test plans, and contract statements.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The creation of proper lower-level requirements is critical.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The provision of only quantitative minimum targets (e.g., Mean Time Between Failure (MTBF) values or failure rates) is not sufficient for different reasons.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Compare this problem with the continuous (re-)balancing of, for example, lower-level-system mass requirements in the development of an aircraft, which is already often a big undertaking.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Notice that in this case, masses do only differ in terms of only some %, are not a function of time, and the data is non-probabilistic and available already in CAD models.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] In the case of reliability, the levels of unreliability (failure rates) may change with factors of decades (multiples of 10) as a result of very minor deviations in design, process, or anything else.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The information is often not available without huge uncertainties within the development phase.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] This makes this allocation problem almost impossible to do in a useful, practical, valid manner that does not result in massive over- or under-specification.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] A pragmatic approach is therefore needed—for example: the use of general levels/classes of quantitative requirements depending only on severity of failure effects.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Also, the validation of results is a far more subjective task than any other type of requirement.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] (Quantitative) reliability parameters—in terms of MTBF—are by far the most uncertain design parameters in any design.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Furthermore, reliability design requirements should drive a (system or part) design to incorporate features that prevent failures from occurring, or limit consequences from failure in the first place.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Not only would it aid in some predictions, this effort would keep from distracting the engineering effort into a kind of accounting work.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] A design requirement should be precise enough so that a designer can "design to" it and can also prove—through analysis or testing—that the requirement has been achieved, and, if possible, within some a stated confidence.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Any type of reliability requirement should be detailed and could be derived from failure analysis (Finite-Element Stress and Fatigue analysis, Reliability Hazard Analysis, FTA, FMEA, Human Factor Analysis, Functional Hazard Analysis, etc.) or any type of reliability testing.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Also, requirements are needed for verification tests (e.g., required overload stresses) and test time needed.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] To derive these requirements in an effective manner, a systems engineering-based risk assessment and mitigation logic should be used.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Robust hazard log systems must be created that contain detailed information on why and how systems could or have failed.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Requirements are to be derived and tracked in this way.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] These practical design requirements shall drive the design and not be used only for verification purposes.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] These requirements (often design constraints) are in this way derived from failure analysis or preliminary tests.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Understanding of this difference compared to only purely quantitative (logistic) requirement specification (e.g., Failure Rate / MTBF target) is paramount in the development of successful (complex) systems.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The maintainability requirements address the costs of repairs as well as repair time.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Testability (not to be confused with test requirements) requirements provide the link between reliability and maintainability and should address detectability of failure modes (on a particular system level), isolation levels, and the creation of diagnostics (procedures).
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] As indicated above, reliability engineers should also address requirements for various reliability tasks and documentation during system development, testing, production, and operation.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] These requirements are generally specified in the contract statement of work and depend on how much leeway the customer wishes to provide to the contractor.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability tasks include various analyses, planning, and failure reporting.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Task selection depends on the criticality of the system as well as cost.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] A safety-critical system may require a formal failure reporting and review process throughout development, whereas a non-critical system may rely on final test reports.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The most common reliability program tasks are documented in reliability program standards, such as MIL-STD-785 and IEEE 1332.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Failure reporting analysis and corrective action systems are a common approach for product/process reliability monitoring.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] However, humans are also very good at detecting such failures, correcting them, and improvising when abnormal situations occur.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Therefore, policies that completely rule out human actions in design and production processes to improve reliability may not be effective.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Some tasks are better performed by humans and some are better performed by machines.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Furthermore, human errors in management; the organization of data and information; or the misuse or abuse of items, may also contribute to unreliability.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] This is the core reason why high levels of reliability for complex systems can only be achieved by following a robust systems engineering process with proper planning and execution of the validation and verification tasks.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] This also includes the careful organization of data and information sharing and creating a "reliability culture", in the same way, that having a "safety culture" is paramount in the development of safety-critical systems.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] For existing systems, it is arguable that any attempt by a responsible program to correct the root cause of discovered failures may render the initial MTBF estimate invalid, as new assumptions (themselves subject to high error levels) of the effect of this correction must be made.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Another practical issue is the general unavailability of detailed failure data, with those available often featuring inconsistent filtering of failure (feedback) data, and ignoring statistical errors (which are very high for rare events like reliability related failures).
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Very clear guidelines must be present to count and compare failures related to different type of root-causes (e.g. manufacturing-, maintenance-, transport-, system-induced or inherent design failures).
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Comparing different types of causes may lead to incorrect estimations and incorrect business decisions about the focus of improvement.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] To perform a proper quantitative reliability prediction for systems may be difficult and very expensive if done by testing.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] At the individual part-level, reliability results can often be obtained with comparatively high confidence, as testing of many sample parts might be possible using the available testing budget.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] However, these tests may lack validity at a system-level due to assumptions made at part-level testing.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] These authors emphasized the importance of initial part- or system-level testing until failure, and to learn from such failures to improve the system or part.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The general conclusion is drawn that an accurate and absolute prediction – by either field-data comparison or testing – of reliability is in most cases not possible.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] An exception might be failures due to wear-out problems such as fatigue failures.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] In the introduction of MIL-STD-785 it is written that reliability prediction should be used with great caution, if not used solely for comparison in trade-off studies.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Design for Reliability (DfR) is a process that encompasses tools and procedures to ensure that a product meets its reliability requirements, under its use environment, for the duration of its lifetime.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] DfR is implemented in the design stage of a product to proactively improve product reliability.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] DfR is often used as part of an overall Design for Excellence (DfX) strategy.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability design begins with the development of a (system) model.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability and availability models use block diagrams and Fault Tree Analysis to provide a graphical means of evaluating the relationships between different parts of the system.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] These models may incorporate predictions based on failure rates taken from historical data.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] While the (input data) predictions are often not accurate in an absolute sense, they are valuable to assess relative differences in design alternatives.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Maintainability parameters, for example Mean time to repair (MTTR), can also be used as inputs for such models.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The most important fundamental initiating causes and failure mechanisms are to be identified and analyzed with engineering tools.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] A diverse set of practical guidance as to performance and reliability should be provided to designers so that they can generate low-stressed designs and products that protect, or are protected against, damage and excessive wear.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Proper validation of input loads (requirements) may be needed, in addition to verification for reliability "performance" by testing.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] One of the most important design techniques is redundancy.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] This means that if one part of the system fails, there is an alternate success path, such as a backup system.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The reason why this is the ultimate design choice is related to the fact that high-confidence reliability evidence for new parts or systems is often not available, or is extremely expensive to obtain.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] By combining redundancy, together with a high level of failure monitoring, and the avoidance of common cause failures; even a system with relatively poor single-channel (part) reliability, can be made highly reliable at a system level (up to mission critical reliability).
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] No testing of reliability has to be required for this.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Redundancy can also be applied in systems engineering by double checking requirements, data, designs, calculations, software, and tests to overcome systematic failures.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Another effective way to deal with reliability issues is to perform analysis that predicts degradation, enabling the prevention of unscheduled downtime events / failures.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] RCM (Reliability Centered Maintenance) programs can be used for this.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] For electronic assemblies, there has been an increasing shift towards a different approach called physics of failure.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] This technique relies on understanding the physical static and dynamic failure mechanisms.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The material or component can be re-designed to reduce the probability of failure and to make it more robust against such variations.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Another common design technique is component derating: i.e. selecting components whose specifications significantly exceed the expected stress levels, such as using heavier gauge electrical wire than might normally be specified for the expected electric current.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Results from these methods are presented during reviews of part or system design, and logistics.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is just one requirement among many for a complex part or system.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Engineering trade-off studies are used to determine the optimum balance between reliability requirements and other constraints.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineers, whether using quantitative or qualitative methods to describe a failure or hazard, rely on language to pinpoint the risks and enable issues to be solved.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The language used must help create an orderly description of the function/item/system and its complex surrounding as it relates to the failure of these functions/items/systems.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Systems engineering is very much about finding the correct words to describe the problem (and related risks), so that they can be readily solved via engineering solutions.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Jack Ring said that a systems engineer's job is to "language the project." (Ring et al.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] 2000) For part/system failures, reliability engineers should concentrate more on the "why and how", rather that predicting "when".
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Understanding "why" a failure has occurred (e.g. due to over-stressed components or manufacturing issues) is far more likely to lead to improvement in the designs and processes used than quantifying "when" a failure is likely to occur (e.g. via determining MTBF).
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] To do this, first the reliability hazards relating to the part/system need to be classified and ordered (based on some form of qualitative and quantitative logic if possible) to allow for more efficient assessment and eventual improvement.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] This is partly done in pure language and proposition logic, but also based on experience with similar items.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] This can for example be seen in descriptions of events in fault tree analysis, FMEA analysis, and hazard (tracking) logs.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] In this sense language and proper grammar (part of qualitative analysis) plays an important role in reliability engineering, just like it does in safety engineering or in-general within systems engineering.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Correct use of language can also be key to identifying or reducing the risks of human error, which are often the root cause of many failures.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] This can include proper instructions in maintenance manuals, operation manuals, emergency procedures, and others to prevent systematic human errors that may result in system failures.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability modeling is the process of predicting or understanding the reliability of a component or system prior to its implementation.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Two types of analysis that are often used to model a complete system's availability behavior including effects from logistics issues like spare part provisioning, transport and manpower are fault tree analysis and reliability block diagrams.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] At a component level, the same types of analyses can be used together with others.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The input for the models can come from many sources including testing; prior operational experience; field data; as well as data handbooks from similar or related industries.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Regardless of source, all model input data must be used with great caution, as predictions are only valid in cases where the same product was used in the same context.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] As such, predictions are often only used to help compare alternatives.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is defined as the probability that a device will perform its intended function during a specified period of time under stated conditions.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] where $f(x)\!$ is the failure probability density function and t is the length of the period of time (which is assumed to start from time zero).
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability applies to a specified period of time.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] In practical terms, this means that a system has a specified chance that it will operate without failure before time $T\!$ .
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering ensures that components and materials will meet the requirements during the specified time.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Note that units other than time may sometimes be used (e.g.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is restricted to operation under stated (or explicitly defined) conditions.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] This constraint is necessary because it is impossible to design a system for unlimited conditions.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] A Mars rover will have different specified conditions than a family car.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The operating environment must be addressed during design and testing.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] That same rover may be required to operate in varying conditions requiring additional scrutiny.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Two notable references on reliability theory and its mathematical and statistical foundations are Barlow, R.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Often, knowledge of the statistical dependence between component failures is unknown or only partially constrained.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] When it is desired to model such incomplete knowledge, reliability theory allows for analyses that characterize ranges or bounds on system failure probabilities rather than unique distributions, particularly for small multi-component systems.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Quantitative requirements are specified using reliability parameters.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The most common reliability parameter is the mean time to failure (MTTF), which can also be specified as the failure rate (this is expressed as a frequency or conditional probability density function (PDF)) or the number of failures during a given period.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] These parameters may be useful for higher system levels and systems that are operated frequently (i.e. vehicles, machinery, and electronic equipment).
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability increases as the MTTF increases.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The MTTF is usually specified in hours, but can also be used with other units of measurement, such as miles or cycles.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Using MTTF values on lower system levels can be very misleading, especially if they do not specify the associated Failures Modes and Mechanisms (The F in MTTF).
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] In other cases, reliability is specified as the probability of mission success.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] For example, reliability of a scheduled aircraft flight can be specified as a dimensionless probability or a percentage, as often used in system safety engineering.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] A special case of mission success is the single-shot device or system.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] These are devices or systems that remain relatively dormant and only operate once.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Examples include automobile airbags, thermal batteries and missiles.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Single-shot reliability is specified as a probability of one-time success or is subsumed into a related parameter.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] Single-shot missile reliability may be specified as a requirement for the probability of a hit.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] For such systems, the probability of failure on demand (PFD) is the reliability measure – this is actually an "unavailability" number.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] The PFD is derived from failure rate (a frequency of occurrence) and mission time for non-repairable systems.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] For repairable systems, it is obtained from failure rate, mean-time-to-repair (MTTR), and test interval.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] This measure may not be unique for a given system as this measure depends on the kind of demand.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] In addition to system level requirements, reliability requirements may be specified for critical subsystems.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p01] In most cases, reliability parameters are specified with appropriate statistical confidence intervals.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] The purpose of **reliability testing** or **reliability verification** is to discover potential problems with the design as early as possible and, ultimately, provide confidence that the system meets its reliability requirements.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] The reliability of the product in all environments such as expected use, transportation, or storage during the specified lifespan should be considered.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability verification is also called reliability testing, which refers to the use of modeling, statistics, and other methods to evaluate the reliability of the product based on the product's life span and expected performance.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Most product on the market requires reliability testing, such as automotive, integrated circuit, heavy machinery used to mine nature resources, Aircraft auto software.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability testing may be performed at several levels and there are different types of testing.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Complex systems may be tested at component, circuit board, unit, assembly, subsystem and system levels.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] (The test level nomenclature varies among applications.) For example, performing environmental stress screening tests at lower levels, such as piece parts or small assemblies, catches problems before they cause failures at higher levels.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Testing proceeds during each level of integration through full-up system testing, developmental testing, and operational testing, thereby reducing program risk.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] However, testing does not mitigate unreliability risk.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] With each test both statistical type I and type II errors could be made, depending on sample size, test time, assumptions and the needed discrimination ratio.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] There is risk of incorrectly rejecting a good design (type I error) and the risk of incorrectly accepting a bad design (type II error).
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] It is not always feasible to test all system requirements.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Some systems are prohibitively expensive to test; some failure modes may take years to observe; some complex interactions result in a huge number of possible test cases; and some tests require the use of limited test ranges or other resources.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] In such cases, different approaches to testing can be used, such as (highly) accelerated life testing, design of experiments, and simulations.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] The desired level of statistical confidence also plays a role in reliability testing.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Statistical confidence is increased by increasing either the test time or the number of items tested.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability test plans are designed to achieve the specified reliability at the specified confidence level with the minimum number of test units and test time.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Different test plans result in different levels of risk to the producer and consumer.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] The desired reliability, statistical confidence, and risk levels for each side influence the ultimate test plan.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] The customer and developer should agree in advance on how reliability requirements will be tested.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] A key aspect of reliability testing is to define "failure".
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Although this may seem obvious, there are many situations where it is not clear whether a failure is really the fault of the system.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Variations in test conditions, operator differences, weather and unexpected situations create differences between the customer and the system developer.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] One strategy to address this issue is to use a scoring conference process.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] A scoring conference includes representatives from the customer, the developer, the test organization, the reliability organization, and sometimes independent observers.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] The scoring conference process is defined in the statement of work.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Each test case is considered by the group and "scored" as a success or failure.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] This scoring is the official result used by the reliability engineer.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] As part of the requirements phase, the reliability engineer develops a test strategy with the customer.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] The test strategy makes trade-offs between the needs of the reliability organization, which wants as much data as possible, and constraints such as cost, schedule and available resources.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Test plans and procedures are developed for each reliability test, and results are documented.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability testing is common in the Photonics industry.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Examples of reliability tests of lasers are life test and burn-in.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] These tests consist of the highly accelerated aging, under controlled conditions, of a group of lasers.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] The data collected from these life tests are used to predict laser life expectancy under the intended operating characteristics.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] The product life span can be split into four different for analysis.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Useful life is the estimated economic life of the product, which is defined as the time can be used before the cost of repair do not justify the continue use to the product.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Warranty life is the product should perform the function within the specified time period.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Design life is where during the design of the product, designer take into consideration on the life time of competitive product and customer desire and ensure that the product do not result in customer dissatisfaction.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability test requirements can follow from any analysis for which the first estimate of failure probability, failure mode or effect needs to be justified.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Evidence can be generated with some level of confidence by testing.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] With software-based systems, the probability is a mix of software and hardware-based failures.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Testing reliability requirements is problematic for several reasons.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] A single test is in most cases insufficient to generate enough statistical data.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Multiple tests or long-duration tests are usually very expensive.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Some tests are simply impractical, and environmental conditions can be hard to predict over a systems life-cycle.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineering is used to design a realistic and affordable test program that provides empirical evidence that the system meets its reliability requirements.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Statistical confidence levels are used to address some of these concerns.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] A certain parameter is expressed along with a corresponding confidence level: for example, an MTBF of 1000 hours at 90% confidence level.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] From this specification, the reliability engineer can, for example, design a test with explicit criteria for the number of hours and number of failures until the requirement is met or failed.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] The combination of required reliability level and required confidence level greatly affects the development cost and the risk to both the customer and producer.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Care is needed to select the best combination of requirements—e.g. cost-effectiveness.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability testing may be performed at various levels, such as component, subsystem and system.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] For systems that must last many years, accelerated life tests may be needed.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] A systematic approach to reliability testing is to, first, determine reliability goal, then do tests that are linked to performance and determine the reliability of the product.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] A reliability verification test in modern industries should clearly determine how they relate to the product's overall reliability performance and how individual tests impact the warranty cost and customer satisfaction.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] The purpose of accelerated life testing (ALT test) is to induce field failure in the laboratory at a much faster rate by providing a harsher, but nonetheless representative, environment.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] In such a test, the product is expected to fail in the lab just as it would have failed in the field—but in much less time.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Software reliability is a special aspect of reliability engineering.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] It focuses on foundations and techniques to make software more reliable, i.e., resilient to faults.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] System reliability, by definition, includes all parts of the system, including hardware, software, supporting infrastructure (including critical external interfaces), operators and procedures.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Traditionally, reliability engineering focuses on critical hardware parts of the system.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Since the widespread use of digital integrated circuit technology, software has become an increasingly critical part of most electronics and, hence, nearly all present day systems.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Therefore, software reliability has gained prominence within the field of system reliability.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] There are significant differences, however, in how software and hardware behave.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Most hardware unreliability is the result of a component or material failure that results in the system not performing its intended function.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Repairing or replacing the hardware component restores the system to its original operating state.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] However, software does not fail in the same sense that hardware fails.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Instead, software unreliability is the result of unanticipated results of software operations.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Even relatively small software programs can have astronomically large combinations of inputs and states that are infeasible to exhaustively test.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Restoring software to its original state only works until the same combination of inputs and states results in the same unintended result.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Software reliability engineering must take this into account.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] As with hardware, software reliability depends on good requirements, design and implementation.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Software reliability engineering relies heavily on a disciplined software engineering process to anticipate and design against unintended consequences.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] There is more overlap between software quality engineering and software reliability engineering than between hardware quality and reliability.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] A good software development plan is a key aspect of the software reliability program.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] The software development plan describes the design and coding standards, peer reviews, unit tests, configuration management, software metrics and software models to be used during software development.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] In modern distributed and microservices-based systems, reliability considerations increasingly extend beyond component-level correctness to include the behavior of applications at the business-logic level.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] It addresses scenarios in which individual system components may appear operational, while failures arise from service interactions or logic errors, potentially leading to degraded user experience or incorrect outcomes.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Practices associated with application-level reliability include end-to-end observability, synthetic transaction testing, and validation of business-critical processes, complementing traditional infrastructure-focused reliability methods.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] A common reliability metric is the number of software faults per line of code (FLOC), usually expressed as faults per thousand lines of code.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] This metric, along with software execution time, is key to most software reliability models and estimates.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] The theory is that the software reliability increases as the number of faults (or fault density) decreases.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Establishing a direct connection between fault density and mean-time-between-failure is difficult, however, because of the way software faults are distributed in the code, their severity, and the probability of the combination of inputs necessary to encounter the fault.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Nevertheless, fault density serves as a useful indicator for the reliability engineer.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Other software metrics, such as complexity, are also used.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] This metric remains controversial, since changes in software development and verification practices can have dramatic impact on overall defect rates.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Software testing is an important aspect of software reliability.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Even the best software development process results in some software faults that are nearly undetectable until tested.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Software is tested at several levels, starting with individual units, through integration and full-up system testing.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] All phases of testing, software faults are discovered, corrected, and re-tested.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability estimates are updated based on the fault density and other metrics.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] At a system level, mean-time-between-failure data can be collected and used to estimate reliability.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Unlike hardware, performing exactly the same test on exactly the same software configuration does not provide increased statistical confidence.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Instead, software reliability uses different metrics, such as code coverage.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] The Software Engineering Institute's capability maturity model is a common means of assessing the overall software development process for reliability and quality purposes.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Structural reliability or the reliability of structures is the application of reliability theory to the behavior of structures.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] It is used in both the design and maintenance of different types of structures including concrete and steel structures.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] In structural reliability studies both loads and resistances are modeled as probabilistic variables.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Using this approach the probability of failure of a structure is calculated.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability for safety and reliability for availability are often closely related.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Lost availability of an engineering system can cost money.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] If a subway system is unavailable the subway operator will lose money for each hour the system is down.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] The subway operator will lose more money if safety is compromised.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] The definition of reliability is tied to a probability of not encountering a failure.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] A failure can cause loss of safety, loss of availability or both.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] It is undesirable to lose safety or availability in a critical system.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineering is concerned with overall minimisation of failures that could lead to financial losses for the responsible entity, whereas safety engineering focuses on minimising a specific set of failure types that in general could lead to loss of life, injury or damage to equipment.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Safety engineering is often highly specific, relating only to certain tightly regulated industries, applications, or areas.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] It primarily focuses on system safety hazards that could lead to severe accidents including: loss of life; destruction of equipment; or environmental damage.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] As such, the related system functional reliability requirements are often extremely high.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Although it deals with unwanted failures in the same sense as reliability engineering, it, however, has less of a focus on direct costs, and is not concerned with post-failure repair actions.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Another difference is the level of impact of failures on society, leading to a tendency for strict control by governments or regulatory bodies (e.g. nuclear, aerospace, defense, rail and oil industries).
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Safety can be increased using a 2oo2 cross checked redundant system.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Availability can be increased by using "1oo2" (1 out of 2) redundancy at a part or system level.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] If both redundant elements disagree the more permissive element will maximize availability.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] A 1oo2 system should never be relied on for safety.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Fault-tolerant systems often rely on additional redundancy (e.g.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] 2oo3 voting logic) where multiple redundant elements must agree on a potentially unsafe action before it is performed.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] This increases both availability and safety at a system level.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] This is common practice in aerospace systems that need continued availability and do not have a fail-safe mode.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] The above example of a 2oo3 fault tolerant system increases both mission reliability as well as safety.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] However, the "basic" reliability of the system will in this case still be lower than a non-redundant (1oo1) or 2oo2 system.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Basic reliability engineering covers all failures, including those that might not result in system failure, but do result in additional cost due to: maintenance repair actions; logistics; spare parts etc.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] For example, replacement or repair of 1 faulty channel in a 2oo3 voting system, (the system is still operating, although with one failed channel it has actually become a 2oo2 system) is contributing to basic unreliability but not mission unreliability.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] As an example, the failure of the tail-light of an aircraft will not prevent the plane from flying (and so is not considered a mission failure), but it does need to be remedied (with a related cost, and so does contribute to the basic unreliability levels).
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] When using fault tolerant (redundant) systems or systems that are equipped with protection functions, detectability of failures and avoidance of common cause failures becomes paramount for safe functioning and/or mission reliability.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality often focuses on manufacturing defects during the warranty phase.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability looks at the failure intensity over the whole life of a product or engineering system from commissioning to decommissioning.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Six Sigma has its roots in statistical control in quality of manufacturing.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineering is a specialty part of systems engineering.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] The systems engineering process is a discovery process that is often unlike a manufacturing process.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] A manufacturing process is often focused on repetitive activities that achieve high quality outputs with minimum cost and time.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] The everyday usage term "quality of a product" is loosely taken to mean its inherent degree of excellence.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] In industry, a more precise definition of quality as "conformance to requirements or specifications at the start of use" is used.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Assuming the final product specification adequately captures the original requirements and customer/system needs, the quality level can be measured as the fraction of product units shipped that meet specifications.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Manufactured goods quality often focuses on the number of warranty claims during the warranty period.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality is a snapshot at the start of life through the warranty period and is related to the control of lower-level product specifications.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] This includes time-zero defects i.e. where manufacturing mistakes escaped final Quality Control.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] In theory the quality level might be described by a single fraction of defective products.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability, as a part of systems engineering, acts as more of an ongoing assessment of failure rates over many years.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Theoretically, all items will fail over an infinite period of time.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Defects that appear over time are referred to as reliability fallout.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] To describe reliability fallout a probability model that describes the fraction fallout over time is needed.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] This is known as the life distribution model.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Some of these reliability issues may be due to inherent design issues, which may exist even though the product conforms to specifications.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Even items that are produced perfectly will fail over time due to one or more failure mechanisms (e.g. due to human error or mechanical, electrical, and chemical factors).
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] These reliability issues can also be influenced by acceptable levels of variation during initial production.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality and reliability are, therefore, related to manufacturing.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability is more targeted towards clients who are focused on failures throughout the whole life of the product such as the military, airlines or railroads.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Items that do not conform to product specification will generally do worse in terms of reliability (having a lower MTTF), but this does not always have to be the case.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] The full mathematical quantification (in statistical models) of this combined relation is in general very difficult or even practically impossible.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] In cases where manufacturing variances can be effectively reduced, six sigma tools have been shown to be useful to find optimal process solutions which can increase quality and reliability.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Six Sigma may also help to design products that are more robust to manufacturing induced failures and infant mortality defects in engineering systems and manufactured product.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] In contrast with Six Sigma, reliability engineering solutions are generally found by focusing on reliability testing and system design.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Furthermore, reliability engineering uses system-level solutions, like designing redundant and fault-tolerant systems for situations with high availability needs (see Reliability engineering vs Safety engineering above).
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Note: A "defect" in six-sigma/quality literature is not the same as a "failure" (Field failure | e.g. fractured item) in reliability.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] A six-sigma/quality defect refers generally to non-conformance with a requirement (e.g. basic functionality or a key dimension).
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Items can, however, fail over time, even if these requirements are all fulfilled.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality is generally not concerned with asking the crucial question "are the requirements actually correct?", whereas reliability is.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Once systems or parts are being produced, reliability engineering attempts to monitor, assess, and correct deficiencies.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Monitoring includes electronic and visual surveillance of critical parameters identified during the fault tree analysis design stage.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Data collection is highly dependent on the nature of the system.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Most large organizations have quality control groups that collect failure data on vehicles, equipment and machinery.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Consumer product failures are often tracked by the number of returns.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] For systems in dormant storage or on standby, it is necessary to establish a formal surveillance program to inspect and test random samples.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Any changes to the system, such as field upgrades or recall repairs, require additional reliability testing to ensure the reliability of the modification.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Since it is not possible to anticipate all the failure modes of a given system, especially ones with a human element, failures will occur.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] The reliability program also includes a systematic root cause analysis that identifies the causal relationships involved in the failure such that effective corrective actions may be implemented.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] When possible, system failures and corrective actions are reported to the reliability engineering organization.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Some of the most common methods to apply to a reliability operational assessment are failure reporting, analysis, and corrective action systems (FRACAS).
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] This systematic approach develops a reliability, safety, and logistics assessment based on failure/incident reporting, management, analysis, and corrective/preventive actions.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Organizations today are adopting this method and utilizing commercial systems (such as Web-based FRACAS applications) that enable them to create a failure/incident data repository from which statistics can be derived to view accurate and genuine reliability, safety, and quality metrics.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] It is extremely important for an organization to adopt a common FRACAS system for all end items.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Also, it should allow test results to be captured in a practical way.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Failure to adopt one easy-to-use (in terms of ease of data-entry for field engineers and repair shop engineers) and easy-to-maintain integrated system is likely to result in a failure of the FRACAS program itself.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Some of the common outputs from a FRACAS system include Field MTBF, MTTR, spares consumption, reliability growth, failure/incidents distribution by type, location, part no., serial no., and symptom.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] The use of past data to predict the reliability of new comparable systems/items can be misleading as reliability is a function of the context of use and can be affected by small changes in design/manufacturing.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Systems of any significant complexity are developed by organizations of people, such as a commercial company or a government agency.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] The reliability engineering organization must be consistent with the company's organizational structure.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] For small, non-critical systems, reliability engineering may be informal.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] As complexity grows, the need arises for a formal reliability function.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Because reliability is important to the customer, the customer may even specify certain aspects of the reliability organization.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] There are several common types of reliability organizations.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] The project manager or chief engineer may employ one or more reliability engineers directly.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] In larger organizations, there is usually a product assurance or specialty engineering organization, which may include reliability, maintainability, quality, safety, human factors, logistics, etc.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] In such case, the reliability engineer reports to the product assurance manager or specialty engineering manager.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] In some cases, a company may wish to establish an independent reliability organization.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] This is desirable to ensure that the system reliability, which is often expensive and time-consuming, is not unduly slighted due to budget and schedule pressures.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] In such cases, the reliability engineer works for the project day-to-day, but is actually employed and paid by a separate organization within the company.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Because reliability engineering is critical to early system design, it has become common for reliability engineers, however, the organization is structured, to work as part of an integrated product team.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Some universities offer graduate degrees in reliability engineering.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Other reliability professionals typically have an engineering, statistics, math, or physics degree from a university or college program.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Many engineering programs offer reliability courses, and some universities have entire reliability engineering programs.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] A reliability engineer must be registered as a professional engineer by the state or province by law, but not all reliability professionals are engineers.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineers are required in systems where public safety is at risk.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] There are many professional conferences and industry training programs available for reliability engineers.
[src:do-254/reliability-engineering-p02] Several professional organizations exist for reliability engineers, including the American Society for Quality Reliability Division (ASQ-RD), the IEEE Reliability Society, the American Society for Quality (ASQ), and the Society of Reliability Engineers (SRE).
